  "prompt": "While inside a mother's womb, the baby gets oxygen through the placenta. How is this balanced so both the mother and the baby get enough oxygen?",
  "response": "The exchange of oxygen between the mother and the fetus is a complex process that occurs through the placenta. Here's how it works:\n\n1. Separate Circulatory Systems\n- The mother's and baby's blood do NOT directly mix\n- They are separated by a thin membrane in the placenta\n\n2. Oxygen Transfer Mechanism\n- Maternal blood is rich in oxygen\n- This oxygen diffuses across the placental membrane into the fetal blood\n- The process works similar to how oxygen crosses lung membranes\n\n3. Hemoglobin Adaptation\n- Fetal hemoglobin has a higher affinity for oxygen compared to adult hemoglobin\n- This allows the fetus to extract oxygen more efficiently from maternal blood\n\n4. Placental Circulation\n- The placenta has a large surface area for efficient gas exchange\n- Blood flows in opposite directions to maximize oxygen transfer\n- This creates a countercurrent exchange system\n\n5. Oxygen Priority\n- The mother's body naturally prioritizes oxygen transfer to the fetus\n- If oxygen is limited, the baby's needs are met first\n\n6. Biological Regulation\n- Hormones and chemical signals help regulate oxygen transfer\n- This ensures balanced oxygen supply based on the baby's needs\n\nThis sophisticated mechanism ensures the developing fetus receives adequate oxygen throughout pregnancy.",
